Your line

    copy = Enumerable.Range(0, copyIList.Count)
        .Select(i =&gt; copyIList[i])
        .ToArray();

Is actually:

    copy = Enumerable.Range(0, copyIList.Count)
        .Select&lt;int, object&gt;(i =&gt; copyIList[i])
        .ToArray&lt;object&gt;();

The compiler knows that `copyIList` is an IList. When you do `copyIList[i]`, you access [IList&#39;s indexer](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.collections.ilist.item?view=netframework-4.8), which returns `object`. So the `Select` returns an `IEnumerable&lt;object&gt;`, and the `ToArray()` therefore generates an `object[]`.

Array has a [Clone method](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.array.clone?view=netframework-4.8) which will make your life easier:

    ((Array)original).Clone();

Failing that, you can instantiate a new array with [`Array.CreateInstance`](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.array.createinstance?view=netframework-4.8#System_Array_CreateInstance_System_Type_System_Int32_).

----------------------

For the List case, it would be easier to use List&#39;s constructor which takes another list to copy:

    public object Get_ListCopy(object original)
    {
        Type elementType = original.GetType().GetGenericArguments()[0];
        Type listType = typeof(List&lt;&gt;).MakeGenericType(elementType);

        object copy = Activator.CreateInstance(listType, new[] { original });
        return copy;
    }

