You can use the function `str.isdigit()`

```python
dictionary_in_question = {&quot;name&quot; : &quot;Value&quot;, &quot;1&quot;:&quot;1.3&quot;}
new_dict = {}
for k,v in dictionary_in_question.items():
     if k.isdigit() or v.isdigit():
         new_dict[k] = v

```

You can use [isdigit()][1] to see if all characters of a string are digits:

    {int(k): float(v) for (k,v) in dictionary_in_question.items() if k.isdigit()}

Prints:

    {1: 1.3}

In case you need the value as integer as well, you can convert the value by `int(float(v))`


  [1]: https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str.isdigit

### Use [`.isnumeric()`][1] to check if each key is numeric

- This method uses a [dictionary comprehension][2]

```python
my_dict = {&quot;name&quot; : &quot;Value&quot;, &quot;1&quot;:&quot;1.3&quot;}

num_dict = {k: v for k, v in my_dict.items() if k.isnumeric()}

print(num_dict)

&gt;&gt;&gt; {&#39;1&#39;: &#39;1.3&#39;}
```


  [1]: https://docs.python.org/3/library/stdtypes.html#str.isnumeric
  [2]: https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0274/

